<paragraph blockId="32.[189,1399,1222,1333]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
The 
<typeStatus box="[246,297,1270,1296]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">type</typeStatus>
specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1923" box="[464,695,1270,1296]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhodoleuca">
<emphasis box="[464,695,1270,1296]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Centris rhodoleuca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
looks very different from males of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Snelling" baseAuthorityYear="1974" box="[1137,1284,1270,1296]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhodopus">
<emphasis box="[1137,1284,1270,1296]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">C. rhodopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it is actually conspecific, corresponding to a metander male.
</paragraph>
